<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Losses close a turbulent week
for Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
A combination of profit-taking, expiration-related trading and sell programs
meant US share prices ended a tumultuous week with sharp losses, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 30.45 at 3,492.83.
The more broadly based Standard&amp;Poor's 500 ended 4.75 lower at 445.84, while
the Amex composite finished down 0.57 at 432.86, and the Nasdaq composite
down 3.14 at 694.29. Trading volume on the NYSE was 273m shares.
Following Wednesday and Thursday's record-breaking gains - the Dow climbed
79 points over the two days - some investors chose to book some of their
profits as soon as trading opened, contributing to an early 20-point decline
in the Dow. The fact that a large number of analysts remained suspicious of
the market's strength, believing that the buying was an over-reaction to the
absence of an interest rate hike by the Federal Reserve, only hastened the
rush to take some profits.
The monthly expiration of stock and stock index futures also sparked some
early selling. Although share prices quickly rallied from early technical
selling, stocks were hit later in the day by fresh declines in bond prices.
The benchmark 30-year government bond fell almost  1/2 point, sending the
yield back over 7 per cent. A number of afternoon sell programs, and news of
higher gold prices, subsequently pushed stocks to new lows late in the
session. AT&amp;T received an early lift from securities house Alex Brown, which
upgraded its rating on the stock and raised its earnings growth estimates.
The recommendation helped AT&amp;T gain Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 60 3/4 , but by
the close the shares had slipped back to end down Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 59
1/8 . Trading volume was heavy at 3.3m shares.
Other leading stocks, under pressure from profit-taking, were also lower.
They included Coca-Cola, down Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 40 7/8 , Pepsico,
down Dollars 1 at Dollars 36 3/4 , Walt Disney, Dollars  7/8 lower at
Dollars 43 1/8 , and Time Warner, down Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 36 1/8 .
Storage Technology surged Dollars 1 to Dollars 40 5/8 in volume of 1m shares
after the company said it had agreed to acquire Amperif, a privately held
storage system manufacturer, for Dollars 83.6m.
The news that Storage Tech also plans to start shipping its long-delayed
Iceberg storage system by the fourth quarter of this year also buoyed the
stock.
May Department Stores rose Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 75 1/4 after the retailer
announced plans to invest Dollars 4.6bn over next five years on new stores.
The company also announced a 2-for-1 stock split.
Canada
TORONTO stocks closed little changed in extremely heavy trading. The
composite index rose 4.40 points, or 0.11 per cent, to 3835.99, with
advances leading declines 378 to 294. On the week, the index was up about 22
points. Volume, the third highest on record, was increased by extremely
heavy trading in Encor Inc. (about 14.1m shares) and American Eagle
Petroleums (about 12.8m shares), which are involved in separate merger
transactions. Volume reached 87,446,000 shares, above yesterday's 83,375,000
shares, and trading value was CDollars 625.6m against CDollars 541.7m.
</TEXT>
