FT  22 MAY 93 / Letter: Lavishness of dinner in eye of the beholder
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr DAVID IVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your reporter David Owen writes of a 'lavish dinner' to mark the
chancellor's 21st anniversary as member of parliament for
Kingston-upon-Thames ('Knives out for Lamont again', May 15).
As somebody who was also there I can confirm that it was a very pleasant and
convivial occasion, but 'lavish dinner'? - it depends on one's standards.
David Owen also refers to 'days when Conservative governments used sometimes
to win mid-term by-elections'. In fact, Norman Lamont won the Kingston
by-election in May 1972 with a negligible swing against a Conservative
government nearly two years into office. This was attributable to his
impressive qualities as a candidate, the legacy of the retiring member John
Boyd-Carpenter, and an efficient Conservative organisation with more than
6,000 members.
