<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAY 93 / International Company News: NZ unit matches expectations
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BANK of New Zealand yesterday announced an unaudited operating tax-paid
profit of NZ134.6m (USDollars 74.8m) for the year to March 31, which the new
owners, National Bank of Australia, said was in line with expectations.
The result is not comparable with last year's profit of NZDollars 172m as
NAB changed the company's accounting policies in November when it bought the
bank for NZDollars 1.45bn. It said then that the changes were being made to
reflect its own accounting and provisioning policies. This led to an
abnormal item of NZDollars 277.2m after tax. If the abnormal item is
included, BNZ made a loss of NZDollars 151.3m.
The managing director, Mr Bob Prowse, said the results reflected reduced
income from treasury-related activities such as securities and foreign
exchange trading, where the bank was adopting a more cautious approach. He
said trading margins had tightened significantly during late 1992 and early
1993.
</TEXT>
